For each i:

If i is equal to count (the current digit count of N):

   if i is odd, then add (N - 10^(i-1) +1) to ans. Else (i is not the last digit):

   if i is 1: add 9

   else if i is odd: add 9*10^(i-1) (since 10^i -10^(i-1) = 9*10^{i-1}) Wait, in Java code, for i not equal to count, and i%2 ==1 (except i=1): The code does ans += (Math.pow(10,i) - Math.pow(10,i-1)), which is exactly 9*10^{i-1}. So in Fortran, we can compute that as 9*10**(i-1). But for the last term (i=count), when i is odd, we add (N - 10^{i-1} +1). Because 10^{i-1} is the first number with i digits, so numbers from 10^{i-1} to N contribute (N - 10^{i-1} +1) numbers. So in Fortran, the steps are: Initialize ans=0, count the digits of N (sum from first part). Then loop over i from 1 to count:

   if i == count:

      if mod(i,2) ==1 then:

          ans = ans + (N - 10**(i-1) +1)

   else:

      if i ==1 then:

          ans = ans +9

      else if mod(i,2) ==1 then:

          ans = ans + 9*10**(i-1)

      else:

          do nothing?

Because in the else part of the Java code, the code only adds when i is odd. Wait, in the Java code's else block (when i is not the last digit):

          if (i ==1) add 9

          else if (i%2 ==1) add the term. So for even i (other than 1?), nothing is added here. So in Fortran, for each i from 1 to count:

   if i is the last digit count:

      check if i is odd, add the partial.

   else:

      if i is 1: add 9

      else if i is odd: add 9*10^{i-1}

      else: do nothing. So that's the logic.
